text:
Park Avenue, east side, between 57th and 58th Streets, showing Ritz Tower apartment hotel, on N. E. corner of 57th Street, practically completed.
The building on the N. E. corner of 58th Street is also fairly new, replacing two old Garages.
Notice traffic signal tower at 57th Street, of type shortly to be discontinued.
In right background is the Queensboro Bridge at 59th Street, and in the left background, dimly seen, the Hell Gate Bridge.
1926.

Brown Brothers, Photographers.

A general view of the midtown Manhattan zone east of Madison Avenue as photographed southeastward from the Ritz Tower at 57th Street and Park Avenue. Madison Ave. runs diagonally across the foreground. In the background is the East River and its Brooklyn-Queens shore. The large white building at the right is the Hotel Ambassador.

About 1927

Ewing Galloway
title: General view - [Midtown Manhattan - Madison Avenue.]

text:
57th Street, north side, west from Park Avenue. In the centre is the Central Presbyterian Church, which later this same year will be demolished for the erection of the Fuller Building. April 9, 1929.

P.L. Sperr.

57th Street, north side, west from Park Avenue. The tall building in the centre is the new Fuller Building, Madison Avenue at the N.E. corner of 57th Street.
1930.
Ewing Galloway.

Park Avenue, north from 57th Street, showing faces of buildings on east side of the avenue.
Note on the N.E. corner of 57th Street the Ritz Tower Apartments (1926) and on S.E. corner of 59th Street, the old Arion Society Building (1887).

About 1931.

Ewing Galloway, Photographer.

Park Ave., east side, south from, but not including East 57th Street. Also shown across the sky line, is the R.C.A. Bldg., the Waldorf Astoria Hotel and the Grand Central Bldg.

June 11, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.
